long_desc.thetext:
The current form API (qx.ui.form.IFromElement) has several problems, which make it hard to work with it:
1. The 'name' property: The interface forces all form widgets to implement this property but its not clear, why it is required at all. Neither the framework nor the qooxdoo demos or applications use it and is is easy to emulate it using "setUserData". It just clutters the interface of form widgets.
2. The 'value' property: This one is problematic. It suggests that the user can write code against this interface without knowing the implementation details of the concrete form widgets. In reality this is not true since form widgets expect different data types as values and even raise exceptions if the passed value has the wrong type. The user is forced to know, which type a concrete form element expects and has to code accordingly. It is for example not possible to set a number as value for a text field, which is reasonable. The user has to manually convert the number to a string. In essence this property does more harm than it does help because is creates the illusion that all form elements have a uniform API, which does not hold.
3. There are classes, which implement the IFomeElement interface, which don't match the semantics of a form element very well. Examples are the List or the RadioGroup classes, where it is not obvious what the value should represent. Both are better off just implementing one of the selection interfaces.
I would suggest replacing the vague IFromElement with a collection of more concrete interfaces. The widgets than can choose, which interface does make sense for them. This could further help to maintain a consistent API throughout the framework.

The interface is basically needed for any type of serialization and may be better named IFormSerialization instead of IFormElement. To serialize a form of different fields it's essential to have a name field and a value field to pass the data into simple key-value maps. I still think that's a good idea. In the new Collection classes the getValue() stuff does similar things than the "value" property, but in this case on simple DOM elements and not on widgets.
The "name" property may also be implemented as a Mixin to be added to all of these widgets as it basically do not need any type of
The interface should even be extended to have a serialize() method to have a common way to deal with the data stored on these fields.
The the demos do not make any use of this interface is a problem with the demos and not with the interface. The essence of this interface is to have options to emulate the way developers deal with classic HTML forms and this may not be that wrong for a browser based widget toolkit as well. There should be definitely demos for this area to show how to send a set of options (maybe some kind of preference dialog) to the server.
Also remember: For the server things like a collection of items (e.g. getSelection()) is pretty useless as it couldn't transfered as JSON in this form and need a translation to be useful at the backend side. This is the reason for having both "name" and "value" properties in this interface.

As Fabian already said, the name property is not really used often in our code (never!). But we stared a survey on the mailing list to see if the community uses this kind of feature. If not, i guess its not worth keeping it.
As for the serialization, we dont even have any mechanism for sending a whole form back to the server. Perhaps thats another topic which needs to be addressed in a separate form widget.

Martin, the reason may be that we do not have any backend service which could react on the saved data. Infact we do not have a single application which really do some kind of store-and-load feature with a backend. Arguring that no example use this kind of serialization when there is not even a single backend related example in the code do not make a lot of sense.
The API itself is useful as most classical and easy form handling is used this way. We will see what the community says but I think there are a lot of users requiring these fields for serialization proposes.
Form serialization is maybe another topic - you are right - but the basics must be available in the form elements to be used for these kind of things.
I guess most of this value/name handling will eventually be done by a the data binding stuff so that's the place where serialization etc. is performed.

Comment from duplicate bug #1865
In order to easily handle forms, it would be very useful if all the form-widgets could be controlled using a common interface. This is especially important, when forms are generated using factory methods. Common tasks, such as serializing and restoring form values, as well as validation could be simplified/automated for all elements.
There is already such an Interface (IFormElement: http://demo.qooxdoo.org/current/apiviewer/#qx.ui.form.IFormElement) which covers already a lot of the important form-element properties. Namely: * enabled (can be used to determine if a value should be sent to the server) * name (the name of the form element) * value (the value that will be sent to the server)
There's another property "checked" which isn't covered by the interface. It is currently being used by "CheckBox" and "ToggleButton". This property is some sort of a special case when it comes to form-elements and can't be adequately handled by using the methods provided by the IFormElement interface.
It's usually sufficient to check an element for it's enabled state to determine if it should be serialized or not. When looking at the CheckBox, one would have to check the "enabled" *and* the "checked" property. In addition to that, all form widgets fire changeValue events on User-Input, whereas CheckBoxes don't. Actually, this behavior is correct, since the value doesn't really change, the thing that changes however is the resulting serialized form.
That being said as preliminary note, i'd suggest to enhance the IFormElement interface in a way, that it covers all the important aspects necessary for successful form handling. Sebastian Werner proposed a new property called "serializable". One could check using "isSerializable" to determine if a form value should be considered for serialization. In case of most Form-Elements this would simply map to the "enabled" property. In case of a CheckBox, it would be defined by "checked" and/or "enabled". There could be other use-cases for this property as well. One could think about a disabled form element that will still be serialized (for example if the user-input should be prevented, but the value should still be sent to the server). Introducing this new property would facilitate such a task.
Other than that, we could also introduce an event called "serializeResultChange" which will be fired whenever the serialization "result" changes. Eg. if a checkbox is being checked, the serialization output *will* change and therefore this event should be fired. Same goes for regular user-input. Separating the value and the serialization-result can have some benefits for current and future form-elements. Mostly value and serialization-result will map to the same value though.
*** Bug 1865 has been marked as a duplicate of this bug. ***

Looks good in my opinion. Impressive writeup. Few comments though:
* I wouldn't make serializable a property though as this is mainly an internal state IMHO. So instead of a property it would just be isSerializable() as a simple getter which dynamically evaluates the state of the widget, respecting the internal things interesting like "enabled" or "checked". * I would suggest to name the event "serializeResultChange" as "changeSerialization" instead to cover typical qooxdoo event names. This event would be really impressive when it bubbles up the parent chain so that it is possible for example to add a listener to the GroupBox or Window which contains form elements.

@Sebastian
Color values can be type of number because of a hex number like 0xFFFFFF. That was the main idea behind that.

But this is currently not supported as a color value... or is it? So when respecting the current implementation they may be strings like in "rgb(200,100,100)" or "black" or "#330033". There is no support for other values currently, so in my opinion it is the best to model the interfaces to this restriction at the moment.
to martin

Christian, Fabian and I just agreed in a meeting concerning the form API, that the serialisation should not be in the layer of the widgets. The task of serializing and sending the data back to the server should be done in for example a data binding layer or something else but not in the ui.

The workflow to get the form API clean and functional should be:
1. Define and agree on a set of from interfaces. 2. Add a buddy property to the qooxdoo label for a binding between form widgets and labels. 3. Add valid and mandatory states to the form widgets appearances. 4. Implement an form manager responsible for a loose coupling of form widgets. 5. Create a form widget using the form manager. This widget should be responsible for creating the widgets and handling the layouting. 6. Write a controller for the form widget which will handle the data binding connections from a model to the form widget and vice versa.

To address the first task of the former posted list, we added some ideas for the implementation of the already posted interfaces:
IExecutable event: execute properties: command memeber: execute
IRange properties: min singleStep pageStep max
INumberForm property API for: numberValue + event
IStringForm property API for: stringValue + event
IDateForm property API for: dateValue + event
IBooleanForm property API for: booleanValue + event

Created attachment 480 Chart showing which widget implements which interface.
Removed the IFrom Interface because it would only contain the enabled property which is already defined in the widget.

We just realized that the handling of null values is also inconsistent in the current form widgets. TextFields do not accept null values while a Spinner for example does. This should be considered in the cleanup of the api too and all form widgets should have a routine for handling null values.
Looks like im going to take it!

Martin, could you also take some typical form widgets into account that may not exist yet, but that would have to fit the proposed form API as well, e.g. tri-state CheckBox bug #963? Are there any others we could think of right now?

Still not sure about the color values "0xFFFFFF" is a completely new format in the web, why not simply use "rgb(100,200,300)" or other CSS allowed values like "#FFFFFF"?
I am also not yet convinced that changing the value of the checkbox from the "real" value (in web context) to the "checked" property is a good idea. Yet it makes sense in some cases but is fundamentally different to the way checkboxes are used in classic HTML pages. In these pages it is possible to have multiple checkboxes with the same name to offer some kind of multi selection (in most backends these separate form elements are automatically merged into an array/list e.g. in PHP). At least this should be documented well in the class description and form documentation on the homepage.
To help these checkboxes work the same way it might be possible to offer some kind of CheckBoxGroup. Something like RadioGroup but for Checkboxes. This could then combine the single Checkboxes to a combined form value useful for serialization prupopses.
What do you think?
That color thing is not meant to be different from he current color values. I just used it because i thought it would work. The idea is to use the standard color values supported by qooxdoo.

I don't think HTML forms are a good model for the qooxdoo widget API. We are much closer to native widget toolkits like Qt or SWT. For this reason I think it is reasonable to make this change. However I share your opinion that something like a check box group could be helpful. For me this is related to the form manager bug.

@Martin: OK I understand.
@Fabian: May be you are right. But this is a conceptual change for the user - at least when he/she comes from HTML or from earlier qooxdoo versions. I just would have it documented in some way that we differ here from traditional HTML. Just in the case someone asks :)
